                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.797/17: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-01-31T11:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 31, 1936—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>14. Your 6, January 9, 11 a.m., second paragraph, and your despatch 1631, January
                        9.<note n="44" xml:id="d914fn44">Latter not printed.</note> For your
                    information the Department <pb facs="1077" n="982" xml:id="pg_982"/> considers
                    that the use of the word “manufactories” in its context in Articles I and II of
                    the Treaty confers on American citizens the indisputable right to manufacture on
                    terms of complete equality with Japanese subjects.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
